post_text:
It’s that time again and due to the COVID-19 pandemic and social distancing guidelines that are in place United Way is planning to make their 12th Annual Stuff the Bus School Supply Drive go VIRTUAL. United Way of San Luis Obispo is also challenging businesses that want to participate to encourage their employees and customers to go online to donate much needed school supplies or to make a donation.

More than ever, many local students and teachers are in need of the supplies necessary to begin the year successfully.

From July 1st through August 15th they will host an online, virtual Stuff the Bus School Supply Donation Drive, just visit www.roonga.com/uwslostuffthebus2020 to make a donation today.

Atascadero Unified School District would like you to mark your calendars for the upcoming recognition of it’s 2020 graduating seniors. The District, in coordination with Atascadero High School, Paloma Creek High School, and A.C.E. Academy are working with the City of Atascadero to honor the graduates on Wednesday, June 3rd, 11:00 a.m.

Administration, staff and students have been working hard to plan a memorable event while still adhering to the public health orders in place. More information will be forthcoming but please mark your calendars now as you will not want to miss this event!

Dear Parents,

As we are in the middle of Spring Break, we wanted to reach out to you to update you on our academic plan for Home Based Learning that will begin at the conclusion of Spring Break (4/1/2020). Please see the attached document for more detailed information of the academic plan. Additionally, we are creating a schedule for the distribution of Chromebooks for students in grades 1-6. School principals will send out each school's schedule early next week.

Thank you all for supporting your child with the alternative learning resources that were shared out last week. We look forward to embarking on this new endeavor together with you.

post_text:
Good Afternoon AUSD Families,

Parents, we want to provide clarity around school closures and AUSD. Rest assured that we are in the process of developing a quality online experience for all children. Currently, it is spring break in our school district and we encourage all parents to utilize the alternative learning resources on our district website and which were previously emailed to all parents.

On April 1st, we will begin extended learning opportunities for all students. Please look for active communication from your schools and teachers on April 1st. As quickly as possible we will be transitioning to home based learning and will be checking out chromebooks and other learning tools to students and families.

Please stay tuned for more information after spring break.
Sorry about any confusion from our previous communication.
Thanks so much for supporting your children during this time.

Monterey Road Elementary Receives Water-Conserving Landscape Award~Congratulations to Monterey Road! They, along with One Cool Earth, will be receiving a Water-Conserving Landscape Award for outstanding contributions and excellence in water conservation on June 12 from Atascadero Mutual Water Company.

﻿Monterey Road planted a Food Forest last year in place of a grass hill. The Food Forest is full of native, drought resistant plants. The students designed the forest and tend to it. The area is also used for outdoor learning experiences. Way to go Monterey Road Mustangs!

post_text: Carrisa Plains Gets Special Visit~During the last week of school, Carrisa Plains Elementary students were completing the finale to their animal report writing. They were visited by Kurt Payne, Director of Curriculum and Instruction, and his three desert tortoises. Mr. Payne is licensed by the State of California to have all three captive bred tortoises. Students were quizzed on their knowledge of identifying the differences between turtles and tortoises. Mr. Payne furthered the lesson using the idea of phenomenon and inquiry from the Next Generation Science Standards and had students discuss tortoise adaptations to their habitat and how human impact has affected the native tortoise population. Students enjoyed getting to feed and handle the tortoises as part of the lesson closure.

post_text: Night of Scholars and Champions~Atascadero High School held it's 49th Annual "Night of Scholars and Champions" Scholarship Award ceremony last night at Ewing Gymnasium. Over $210,000 in scholarships were awarded to 89 graduating seniors by 44 community groups and individuals during the evening. Pictured are the Rotary Club of Atascadero's 13 award winners with a total of $34,000. Congratulations to all of the students on their many achievements.

post_text: College and Career Ready~Thank you to the Atascadero City Manager, Rachelle Rickard, and our city staff for taking the time to meet with all three of Irene McDaniel's AHS Honors Geometry classes during the month of May. Ms. Rickard took the students on a tour of the building to meet with each department. Students learned about careers that use math including finance, engineering, city planning, building inspection, and public works. Ms. Rickard also spoke about the 2003 earthquake and what engineers did to ensure the structure was safe. Our AHS Greyhounds were exposed to several potential career paths helping to make them college and career ready!

post_text:
T.I.P. Graduates~ Congratulations to this year's TIP (Teacher Induction Program) Year 2 Colloquium graduates. New teachers that successfully completed their induction program to clear their credential were honored and celebrated on Monday at the District Office. They worked for two years with a veteran mentor teacher to complete various components of this support program. Each mentor teacher gave a brief surprise speech highlighting the strengths and experiences of the graduate. They also shared their reflections from their culminating project- specifically focused on how it led to student success.
Congratulations
Matt Avila
Lauren Chambers
Michael Clemmensen
Kaylie Edgar
Kristin Gaeta
Julia Harrigan
Sarah Iba
Sally Immel
Jocelyn Johnston
Julie Newton
Rachel Pollard
Rob Robertson
